INTRODUCTION.

The present volume of Wyclif's Miscellanea Plzilosophz'ca, which with the works already published contains all his philosophical writings, whether spurious, doubtful, or authentic, with the exception of his great work De Enwte, is not less interesting than the first, but presents sewer new points of interest. All that I wrote concerning Wyclif's philosophy in my Introductory Essay to the first volume applies of course to the second, as it may also be truly said to apply to every one of his works. It will therefore be unnecessary to write a very elaborate Introduction3 a few remarks concerning the manuscripts, their authenticity and date, and the analysis of the text of each work, seems to be sufficient.
